<subSubSection pageId="7" pageNumber="8" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="7.[151,1437,1467,1890]" pageId="7" pageNumber="8">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,276,1467,1494]" pageId="7" pageNumber="8">Diagnosis:</emphasis>
Both sexes of the genus can be fairly easily diagnosed due to the characteristic sigmoidal shape of the vein 2m-cu (also referred to as the second recurrent vein) of the forewing with the posterior part arcuate outwardly, and anterior part slightly curved inwardly (
<figureCitation box="[626,714,1539,1566]" captionStart="FIGURE 1" captionStartId="8.[151,250,1282,1307]" captionTargetBox="[151,1435,174,1270]" captionTargetId="figure@8.[151,1435,174,1270]" captionTargetPageId="8" captionText="FIGURE 1. Lateral view of forewing (A–B) and posterior view of metapostnotum (C–D). (A) Vein 2m-cu (black arrow) sigmoid in Colletes; (B) vein 2m-cu (black arrow) only slightly arcuate outwards in Rhynchocolletes. (C) Horizontal surface divided into pits by a series of longitudinal carinae (red arrows) and separated from vertical surface by transverse carina (yellow arrow) in Colletes; (D) horizontal surface without longitudinal carinae and separated from vertical surface by a change in slope in Rhynchocolletes. Scale bars = 1mm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/2944505/files/figure.png" pageId="7" pageNumber="8">Fig. 1A</figureCitation>
). In some species of 
<taxonomicName authority="Moure, 1943" authorityName="Moure" authorityYear="1943" box="[945,1278,1540,1566]" class="Insecta" family="Colletidae" genus="Rhynchocolletes" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="8" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[945,1129,1540,1566]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="8">Rhynchocolletes</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="Moure, J. S." box="[1134,1278,1540,1566]" pageId="7" pageNumber="8" pagination="447 - 484" refId="ref58014" refString="Moure, J. S. (1943) Notas sobre abelhas da colec uo Zikan (Hym. Apoidea). Revista de Entomologia, 14, 447 - 484." type="journal article" year="1943">Moure, 1943</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
(sensu 
<bibRefCitation author="Moure, J. S. &amp; Urban, D. &amp; Melo, G. A. R." pageId="7" pageNumber="8" pagination="677 - 691" refId="ref58278" refString="Moure, J. S., Urban, D. &amp; Melo, G. A. R. (2007) Colletini Lepeletier, 1841. In: Moure, J. S., Urban, D. &amp; Melo, G. A. R. (Eds.), Catalogue of Bees (Hymenoptera, Apoidea) in the Neotropical Region. Sociedade Brasileira de Entomologia, Curitiba, pp. 677 - 691." type="book chapter" year="2007">
Moure 
<emphasis box="[151,199,1576,1602]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="8">et al</emphasis>
., 2007
</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation author="Moure, J. S. &amp; Urban, D. &amp; Melo, G. A. R." box="[288,345,1575,1602]" pageId="7" pageNumber="8" pagination="1841" refId="ref58359" refString="Moure, J. S., Urban, D. &amp; Melo, G. A. R. (2012) Colletini Lepeletier, 1841. In: Moure, J. S., Urban, D. &amp; Melo, G. A. R. (Eds.), Catalogue of Bees (Hymenoptera, Apoidea) in the Neotropical Region- online version. Available from: http: // moure. cria. org. br / catalogue? id = 15325 (accessed 12 March 2018)" type="book chapter" year="2012">2012</bibRefCitation>
)—the only other genus of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Lepeletier de Saint Fargeau" authorityYear="1841" box="[640,755,1575,1601]" class="Insecta" family="Colletidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="8" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="subFamily" subFamily="Colletinae">Colletinae</taxonomicName>
with representatives in eastern South America—the posterior part of the 2m-cu vein may be slightly arcuate, however, its anterior part is always straight and thus the vein is never sigmoidal (
<figureCitation box="[279,367,1647,1674]" captionStart="FIGURE 1" captionStartId="8.[151,250,1282,1307]" captionTargetBox="[151,1435,174,1270]" captionTargetId="figure@8.[151,1435,174,1270]" captionTargetPageId="8" captionText="FIGURE 1. Lateral view of forewing (A–B) and posterior view of metapostnotum (C–D). (A) Vein 2m-cu (black arrow) sigmoid in Colletes; (B) vein 2m-cu (black arrow) only slightly arcuate outwards in Rhynchocolletes. (C) Horizontal surface divided into pits by a series of longitudinal carinae (red arrows) and separated from vertical surface by transverse carina (yellow arrow) in Colletes; (D) horizontal surface without longitudinal carinae and separated from vertical surface by a change in slope in Rhynchocolletes. Scale bars = 1mm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/2944505/files/figure.png" pageId="7" pageNumber="8">Fig. 1B</figureCitation>
). 
<taxonomicName authority="Toro &amp; Cabezas, 1977" authorityName="Toro &amp; Cabezas" authorityYear="1977" box="[390,802,1647,1674]" class="Insecta" family="Hymenoptera (awaiting allocation)" genus="Hemicotelles" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="8" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[390,536,1648,1674]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="8">Hemicotelles</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="Toro, H. &amp; Cabezas, V." box="[545,802,1647,1674]" pageId="7" pageNumber="8" pagination="45 - 64" refId="ref60062" refString="Toro, H. &amp; Cabezas, V. (1977) Nuevos generos y especies de Colletini sudamericanos, segunda parte. Anales del Museo de Historia Natural de Valpariso, 10, 45 - 64." type="journal article" year="1977">Toro &amp; Cabezas, 1977</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName authority="Toro &amp; Cabezas, 1978" authorityName="Toro &amp; Cabezas" authorityYear="1978" box="[859,1290,1647,1674]" class="Insecta" family="Colletidae" genus="Xanthocotelles" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="8" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[859,1025,1648,1674]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="8">Xanthocotelles</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="Toro, H. &amp; Cabezas, V." box="[1034,1290,1647,1674]" pageId="7" pageNumber="8" pagination="131 - 148" refId="ref60100" refString="Toro, H. &amp; Cabezas, V. (1978) Nuevos generos y especies de Colletini sudamericanos, segunda parte. Anales del Museo de Historia Natural de Valpariso, 11, 131 - 148." type="journal article" year="1978">Toro &amp; Cabezas, 1978</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
are both endemic to 
<collectingCountry box="[255,316,1683,1709]" name="Chile" pageId="7" pageNumber="8">Chile</collectingCountry>
and western 
<collectingCountry box="[462,573,1683,1709]" name="Argentina" pageId="7" pageNumber="8">Argentina</collectingCountry>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Michener, C. D." box="[588,763,1683,1710]" pageId="7" pageNumber="8" refId="ref57703" refString="Michener, C. D. (2007) Bees of the World. 2 nd Edition. Johns Hopkins University Press, Baltimore, 1016 pp." type="book" year="2007">Michener 2007</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="Moure, J. S. &amp; Urban, D. &amp; Melo, G. A. R." box="[774,977,1684,1710]" pageId="7" pageNumber="8" pagination="677 - 691" refId="ref58278" refString="Moure, J. S., Urban, D. &amp; Melo, G. A. R. (2007) Colletini Lepeletier, 1841. In: Moure, J. S., Urban, D. &amp; Melo, G. A. R. (Eds.), Catalogue of Bees (Hymenoptera, Apoidea) in the Neotropical Region. Sociedade Brasileira de Entomologia, Curitiba, pp. 677 - 691." type="book chapter" year="2007">
Moure 
<emphasis box="[856,905,1684,1710]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="8">et al</emphasis>
. 2007
</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="Ascher, J. S. &amp; Pickering, J." box="[987,1274,1683,1710]" pageId="7" pageNumber="8" refId="ref54891" refString="Ascher, J. S. &amp; Pickering, J. (2018) Discover Life bee species guide and world checklist (Hymenoptera: Apoidea: Anthophila). Available from: http: // www. discoverlife. org / mp / 20 q? guide = Apoidea _ species (accessed 4 January 2018)" type="url" year="2018">Ascher &amp; Pickering 2018</bibRefCitation>
) and therefore cannot be confused with the 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Latreille" authorityYear="1802" box="[472,564,1720,1746]" class="Insecta" family="Colletidae" genus="Colletes" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="8" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[472,564,1720,1746]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="8">Colletes</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
species found in eastern South America. In 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Latreille" authorityYear="1802" box="[1058,1150,1720,1746]" class="Insecta" family="Colletidae" genus="Colletes" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="8" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1058,1150,1720,1746]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="8">Colletes</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, the horizontal surface of the metapostnotum is divided into a series of pits by longitudinal carinae, and is separated from the vertical surface by a transverse carina that may be complete or interrupted medially (
<figureCitation box="[923,1011,1791,1818]" captionStart="FIGURE 1" captionStartId="8.[151,250,1282,1307]" captionTargetBox="[151,1435,174,1270]" captionTargetId="figure@8.[151,1435,174,1270]" captionTargetPageId="8" captionText="FIGURE 1. Lateral view of forewing (A–B) and posterior view of metapostnotum (C–D). (A) Vein 2m-cu (black arrow) sigmoid in Colletes; (B) vein 2m-cu (black arrow) only slightly arcuate outwards in Rhynchocolletes. (C) Horizontal surface divided into pits by a series of longitudinal carinae (red arrows) and separated from vertical surface by transverse carina (yellow arrow) in Colletes; (D) horizontal surface without longitudinal carinae and separated from vertical surface by a change in slope in Rhynchocolletes. Scale bars = 1mm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/2944505/files/figure.png" pageId="7" pageNumber="8">Fig. 1C</figureCitation>
). In 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Moure" authorityYear="1943" box="[1062,1245,1792,1818]" class="Insecta" family="Colletidae" genus="Rhynchocolletes" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="8" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1062,1245,1792,1818]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="8">Rhynchocolletes</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, the longitudinal carinae and transverse carina are absent, and the horizontal and vertical surfaces of metapostnotum are separated from each other only by a change in slope (
<figureCitation box="[636,725,1863,1890]" captionStart="FIGURE 1" captionStartId="8.[151,250,1282,1307]" captionTargetBox="[151,1435,174,1270]" captionTargetId="figure@8.[151,1435,174,1270]" captionTargetPageId="8" captionText="FIGURE 1. Lateral view of forewing (A–B) and posterior view of metapostnotum (C–D). (A) Vein 2m-cu (black arrow) sigmoid in Colletes; (B) vein 2m-cu (black arrow) only slightly arcuate outwards in Rhynchocolletes. (C) Horizontal surface divided into pits by a series of longitudinal carinae (red arrows) and separated from vertical surface by transverse carina (yellow arrow) in Colletes; (D) horizontal surface without longitudinal carinae and separated from vertical surface by a change in slope in Rhynchocolletes. Scale bars = 1mm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/2944505/files/figure.png" pageId="7" pageNumber="8">Fig. 1D</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
